# Nested Classes in Java
   In Java, a nested class is a class defined inside another class.
   It helps in logically grouping classes, improving encapsulation, and making code more readable.
   If we define or declare one class inside another class then such a form is called as “class
    within class or Nested class”
     Using this facility complex data type can be created.
     Nested class is used to access elements of class which is part of another class.


# Types of Nested Classes
Type	                   Description	                     Can Access Outer Class Members?	               Can Be Static?
Static Nested Class	       Declared with static modifier.	    ❌ (Only static members)                        	✅
Non-Static (Inner Class)   Regular inner class (no static).	    ✅ (All members)	                                ❌
Local Inner Class	       Defined inside a method/block.	    ✅ (Only final or effectively final local vars)	    ❌
Anonymous Inner Class	   Unnamed class                     	✅ (Same as local inner class)	                    ❌
                           (used for interfaces/abstract classes).


# Object Creation Syntax

1) Create object of outer class as:
       outerClass obj1 = new outerClass( );
2) Create object of inner class as:
       outerClass.innerClass obj2 = obj1.new innerClass( );
3) Create object of supper inner class as:
       outerClass.innerClass.superinnerClas obj3 = obj2.new superinnerClass( );